[pils: .use? .language system]
><:[module: . compute, .timestamp 2009-04-26T18:01:35.776+02 .language system]><;
><:[module: . compute clans .timestamp 2009-04-26T18:51:24.089+02 .language system]><;
!!
@ [compute] clans

Input: a list of families.
A family is a constant list of one or more members. A member
may occur in several families.

Output: a list of clans.
Each member belongs to exactly one clan. Every family group
is contained in a clan, and all members of a clan are related.

Why:
Useful for grouping related items, based on sparse relation indications.

How:
Family heads are appointed and grouped by shared family members
These grous are clanned (recursively) and clan heads appointed, so
that each family head refers to a clan head. The whole population is
then grouped by the clan heads of their family heads.

For simplicity of ordering, all members are kept in a population list
and the clanning is done with indices.
!!

{ clans: families
| families every {= +& ok|:ok} .:need and:
  :ok
  ;population families splice distinct;
  ( ;index population legs {value := name|:ok ;name .value} singles [ok];
    families every {family|:ok family distinct every (index) order [ok]}
  )
  call
  { families
  | :who :try
    ;heads
      families
      every {family = head . 1|:ok family every {x|:ok x, head}} splice
      distinct groups {x, head| :ok ;name x .value head}
    ;
    ;clanheads
      heads legs {? := ok|:ok . distinct order [ok]} distinct
      call (who)
      every
      { group = clanhead . 1
      | :ok group every {head|:ok ;name head .value clanhead}
      }
      splice groups [ok]
    ;
    population count up groups (heads -> [call: 1] -> clanheads)
    legs {? := ok|:ok}
  }
  { families | :try families every {ok = (x,)|:ok} }
  **=** population
}
><:[module: . compute clans test .timestamp 2009-04-26T18:03:19.541+02 .language system]><;
! Group some connected cities by continent.
{ .test
| :ok
  @ clans
  [ Oslo Stockholm Copenhagen,
    Copenhagen Berlin Vienna Rome,
    London Paris Rome Paris London,
    Washington NewYork,
    Washington Detroit,
    Calcutta Calcutta Calcutta
  ]
}
><:[module: . compute order .timestamp 2009-04-26T18:05:45.682+02 .language system]><;
!!
@ [compute] order: .; items

Input: a list of distinct constant items, and a partial order, mapping
some items to lists of items on which they depend.

Output: the list, reordered so that items are after the items on which
they depend, whenever possible. In case of circular dependencies,
some dependencies will be ignored.

Why:
Useful to construct a build order from dependencies.

How:
The list is processed from the start, to preserve the original order
when possible. For each item that has not already been included,
dependencies are followed recursively.

The implementation is a bit tricky: dependencies are inserted in
the stream by means of a callback that is tunnelled through a
distinct pipe.
!!

{ order: .; = & items
| ;guard items singles [ok] .:need; :ok
  items every {item|:self :ok list := callback: . self .item} .:list
  distinct [call: item]
  every
  { callback: .? .item | :ok item }
  { callback: ..item
  | item call (order) .:need listwise each (guard) every (callback)
  }
}
